1PROC     WYLBUR System Procedures                                                                                          Page    5
0D-Loc  Object Code    Addr1 Addr2  Stmt Lv Lineno    Source Statement           (Hibal 5, Asmedit 3.3)  HLASM R4.0  2004/03/15 12.51
+_____  ______ ____    _____ _____  ____ __ ______    ______ _________
0                                   1001              * LAST UPDATE 7/86
                                    1002              *******************************************************************
                                    1003              **                                                             ****
                                    1004              **                                                              ***
                                    1005              **      HOW TO ADD A SYSTEM PROCEDURE !                          **
                                    1006              ***     ---------------------------------                        **
                                    1007              *****                                                            **
                                    1008              *******************************************************************
                                    1009              *
                                    1010              *  PROCEDURE TO ADD PROCEDURE:
                                    1011              *
                                    1012              *  1. ADD A ENTRY INTO THE SYSTEM PROCEDURE TABLE.
                                    1013              *
                                    1014              *       THIS TABLE (SYSPROCS) IS SEARCHED TO FIND THE ADDRESS
                                    1015              *       OF THE ROUTINE FOR THE SPECIFIED PROCEDURE.
                                    1016              *       PROC.  THE ENTRIES MUST APPEAR IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER.
                                    1017              *       USE THE 'SYSPROC' MACRO TO CREATE A PROPERLY FORMATED
                                    1018              *       ENTRY.
                                    1019              *
                                    1020              *  2. ADD A SYSTEM VARIABLE/PROCEDURE ROUTINE.
                                    1021              *
                                    1022              *       SYSTEM PROCEDURE ROUTINES ARE FOUND AFTER THE
                                    1023              *       SYSTEM PROCEDURE TABLE. THE ROUTINES SHOULD BE
                                    1024              *       PLACED IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER BASED ON THE PROCEDURE
                                    1025              *       KEYWORD.  WORK AND COMMON ROUTINES SHOULD BE PLACED
                                    1026              *       IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER IN THE COMMON/WORK ROUTINES
                                    1027              *       AREA.  THE BASIC ENTRY AND EXIT CONVENTIONS FOR THE
                                    1028              *       SYSTEM PROCEDURE ROUTINES ARE:
                                    1029              *
                                    1030              *       ON ENTRY:
                                    1031              *            R0 - VARIABLE COUNT
                                    1032              *            R1 - ARGUMENT LIST
                                    1033              *            R6 - PROCEDURE VARIABLE RETURN AREA
                                    1034              *                 (AREA WILL INITIALY CONTAINS PROCEDURE NAME)
                                    1035              *
                                    1036              *       ON EXIT:
                                    1037              *            R6 - RETURNED VALUES AREA (SAME AS ON ENTRY)
                                    1038              *           R15 - CC=ZERO, ALL OK
                                    1039              *                 CC=NZ, IF ERROR,,, ERROR MSG TSEG 'D
                                    1040              *
                                    1041              *       THE FORMAT OF THE ARGUMENTS PASSED AND RETURNED IS
                                    1042              *       DESCRIBED BY THE VNENTRY DSECT.  EACH ARGUMENT OCCUPIES
                                    1043              *       A FIXED LENGTH (L'VPARM) ENTRY. THUS EACH INPUT
                                    1044              *       ARGUMENT (IF ANY) CAN BE EASILY FOUND AT A FIXED OFFSET
                                    1045              *       BASED OFF OF R1.   RETURN VALUES ARE BASED OFF OF R6.
                                    1046              *
                                    1047              *       SEVERAL MACROS EXIST TO MAKE THE ADDITION OF ROUTINES
                                    1048              *       EASIER.  TO USE THESE MACROS CERTAIN ADDITIONAL
                                    1049              *       CONVENTIONS MUST BE ADHERED TO.  THESE CONVENTIONS AND
                                    1050              *       THE MACROS ARE DESCRIBED NOW:
                                    1051              *
                                    1052              *   *** AN 'XENTER R0,R8,...' AND AN 'XEXIT R0,R8,LTR ' MUST
                                    1053              *       BE USED TO ENTER AND EXIT THE ROUTINE.
                                    1054              *
                                    1055              *   *** IF THE ROUTINE IS SUCCESSFUL R15 MUST BE RETURNED
                                    1056              *       EQUAL TO ZERO.  IF NOT R15 MUST BE RETURNED AS NON-ZERO
1PROC     WYLBUR System Procedures                                                                                          Page    6
0D-Loc  Object Code    Addr1 Addr2  Stmt Lv Lineno    Source Statement           (Hibal 5, Asmedit 3.3)  HLASM R4.0  2004/03/15 12.51
+_____  ______ ____    _____ _____  ____ __ ______    ______ _________
0                                   1057              *       (4).  ALSO AN APPROPRIATE ERROR MESSAGE MUST BE TSEG'D.
                                    1058              *       DO NOT EXIT VIA CVNEXT OR CVERROR.
                                    1059              *
                                    1060              *   *** THE 'SETARGS' MACRO.
                                    1061              *
                                    1062              *       TO CHECK ENTRY ARGUMENTS, THE 'SETARGS' MACRO IS
                                    1063              *       PROVIDED.  IT TAKES A SINGLE STRING AS A PARAMETER.
                                    1064              *       THE FIRST TWO CHARACTERS OF THIS STRING DEFINE THE
                                    1065              *       MAXIMUM AND MINIMUM NUMBER OF ARGUMENTS THAT THE
                                    1066              *       ROUTINE WILL TAKE.  THE REMAINING CHARACTERS DESCRIBE
                                    1067              *       THE FORMAT THAT THESE ARGUMENTS SHOULD BE CONVERTED TO:
                                    1068              *       S=STRING, I=INTEGER, W=LINE NUMBER, X=DON'T CARE.  FOR
                                    1069              *       AN EXAMPLE SEE THE 'EXAMPLE' ROUTINE.  NOTE THAT THE
                                    1070              *       'SETARGS' MACRO CALLS A SETARGS ROUTINE.  THIS ROUTINE
                                    1071              *       ASSUMES THAT R0,R1 AND R6 ARE THE SAME AS WHEN THE
                                    1072              *       SYSTEM PROCEDURE ROUTINE WAS CALLED.  'SETARGS' ALSO
                                    1073              *       WILL GIVE A NON-ZERO RETURN CODE AND TSEG A ERROR
                                    1074              *       MESSAGE IF THE ARGUMENTS CANNOT BE CONVERTED TO THE
                                    1075              *       REQUIRED FORMAT. THE 'SETARGS' MACRO DOES NOT HANDLE
                                    1076              *       'ARRAYS' OR 'PACKED' NUMBERS.
                                    1077              *
                                    1078              *   *** THE 'BADARG' MACRO
                                    1079              *
                                    1080              *       AN 'INVALID ARGUMENT' MESSAGE IS GENERATED BY THE
                                    1081              *       'BADARG' MACRO.  THE MACRO TAKES A SINGLE
                                    1082              *       NUMBER AS A PARAMETER.  THIS NUMBER IS THE NUMBER OF
                                    1083              *       THE INVALID ARGUMENT.  THIS MACRO REQUIRES THAT R6 AND
                                    1084              *       THE AREA POINTED TO BY R6 BE THE SAME AS WHEN THE
                                    1085              *       SYSTEM PROCEDURE ROUTINE WAS ENTERED.
                                    1086              *
                                    1087              *   *** THE 'PRETVAL' MACRO
                                    1088              *
                                    1089              *       THE 'PRETVAL' MACRO IS USED TO RETURN VALUES TO A
                                    1090              *       PROCEDURE. IT TAKES 3-4 PARAMETERS.  THE FIRST PARM IS
                                    1091              *       THE NUMBER OF THE PARAMETER TO RETURN.  THE SECOND IS
                                    1092              *       THE TYPE OF VALUE TO RETURN.  THIS MAY BE STRING,
                                    1093              *       INTEGER, LINENO, OR BOOLEAN.  ARRAYS AND PACKED NUMBERS
                                    1094              *       MAY NOT BE RETURNED WITH THIS MACRO.  ARGUMENTS 3-4 ARE
                                    1095              *       THE VALUE OF THE PARAMETER. IF THE TYPE IS A STRING:
                                    1096              *       ARGS 3-4 ARE THE STRING LOC, LENGTH; A QUOTED STRING
                                    1097              *       MAY BE RETURNED, THE CONVENTIONS FOR RETURNING A STRING
                                    1098              *       ARE THE SAME AS FOR THE 'MSG' MACRO.  IF THE TYPE IS
                                    1099              *       INTEGER OR LINENO: THE THIRD PARAMETER IS A FULLWORD
                                    1100              *       VALUE.  IF THE TYPE IS BOOLEAN: THE THIRD PARAMTER IS
                                    1101              *       THE WORD 'TRUE' OR THE WORD 'FALSE'.  THIS MACRO
                                    1102              *       REQUIRES THAT R6 BE THE SAME AS WHEN THE SYSTEM
                                    1103              *       VAR/PROC. ROUTINE WAS ENTERED.  FOR EXAMPLES, SEE THE
                                    1104              *       'EXAMPLE' ROUTINE.  OTHER EXAMPLES ARE:
                                    1105              *              PRETVAL 1,STRING,'THIS IS IT'
                                    1106              *              PRETVAL 3,BOOLEAN,TRUE
                                    1107              *              PRETVAL 4,LINENO,L:RETLNO
                                    1108              *       HEY DUDE !! THE PRETVAL MACRO CLOBBERS R15,R0,R1,R2 SO
                                    1109              *       BE CAREFULL.  R15 IS SET TO ZERO AT THE END OF THE
                                    1110              *       PRETVAL MACRO.
                                    1111              *
                                    1112              *   *** THE 'PTRIM' MACRO
1PROC     WYLBUR System Procedures                                                                                          Page    7
0D-Loc  Object Code    Addr1 Addr2  Stmt Lv Lineno    Source Statement           (Hibal 5, Asmedit 3.3)  HLASM R4.0  2004/03/15 12.51
+_____  ______ ____    _____ _____  ____ __ ______    ______ _________
0                                   1113              *
                                    1114              *       THE 'PTRIM' MACRO IS USED TO TRIM TRAILING BLANKS OFF
                                    1115              *       THE END OF RETURNED STINGS.  IT WILL ALSO SET BLANK OR
                                    1116              *       ZEROED STRINGS TO NULL STRINGS.  IT REQUIRES THAT R6 BE
                                    1117              *       THE SAME AS WHEN THE SYSTEM PROCEDURE ROUTINE WAS
                                    1118              *       ENTERED.  IT IS GENERALLY CODED DIRECTLY FOLLOWING THE
                                    1119              *       'PRETVAL STRING,..' MACRO.  THIS MACRO DESTROYS R15-R2.
                                    1120              *       THERE IS NO EXAMPLE,,, SEE 'VTRIM' IN FUNC.
                                    1121              *
                                    1122              *   *** GENERAL ARGUMENT LOADING/CHECKING PROCEDURES
                                    1123              *
                                    1124              *       ARGUMENTS PASSED TO A ROUTINE ARE GENERALLY CHECKED FOR
                                    1125              *       VALIDITY AT THE VERY BEGINING OF THE ROUTINE WITH THE
                                    1126              *       'SETARGS' MACRO.  THE ARGUMENTS ARE THEN LOADED AND
                                    1127              *       CHECKED (WHILE THE ENTRY REGS ARE STILL SET UP)
                                    1128              *       GENERALLY AS FOLLOWS:  (THIS IS AN EXAMPLE ONLY, OH
                                    1129              *       YEAH:)
                                    1130              *
                                    1131              *       PROCXXX  XENTER R0,R8,L'XXWA,LOCAL ENTER ROUTINE
                                    1132              *                ST     R0,XXPRMCNT        SAVE PARM COUNT
                                    1133              *                ST     R6,XXRETPTR        SAVE RETURN AREA POINTER
                                    1134              *        *
                                    1135              *                COMMENT                   GET INPUT PARMS
                                    1136              *                SETARGS '22SI'            2 ARGS: STRING, INTEGER
                                    1137              *                IF    Z,BEGIN             IF ARGS OK,...
                                    1138              *                USING VNENTRY,R5
                                    1139              *                LA    R5,ARG1(R1)         R5 - 1ST ARG POINTER
                                    1140              *                LA    R2,VNSTRLOC         R2 - LOC OF STRING
                                    1141              *                LH    R3,VNSTRLEN         R3 - LEN OF STRING
                                    1142              *                IF    (R3,GT,120),BEGIN
                                    1143              *                BADARG 1                  PRETEND CHECK FOR STR LEN
                                    1144              *                EXIT  PROCXXX
                                    1145              *                END
                                    1146              *                LA    R5,ARG2(R1)         R5 - 2ND ARG POINTER
                                    1147              *                L     R4,VNVALUE          R4 - INTEGER VALUE
                                    1148              *                IF    ((R4,NEG),OR,(R4,GT,120)),BEGIN
                                    1149              *                BADARG 2                  PRETEND CHECK FOR ARG 2
                                    1150              *                EXIT  PROCXXX
                                    1151              *                END
                                    1152              *                ..... AND SO ON
                                    1153              *
                                    1154              *
                                    1155              *                ... END OF ROUTNE, XEXIT ...
                                    1156              *
                                    1157              *
                                    1158              *   *** RETURNING PROCEDURE VALUES,,,
                                    1159              *
                                    1160              *       THE EASY WAY IS WITH THE 'PRETVAL MACRO', BUT THERE ARE
                                    1161              *       OTHER WAYS.  YOU MAY SET UP YOUR OWN RETURN VALUE @R6.
                                    1162              *       SEE VNENTRY DSECT. THE AREA MUST BE CLEARED.  FLAGS
                                    1163              *       MUST BE SET FOR THE VARIABLE TYPE:  STRING, BOOLEAN,
                                    1164              *       NUMBER.  THE VARIABLE VALUE MUST BE SET.  THERE ARE NO
                                    1165              *       EXAMPLES IN PROC, SEE 'FNPI' IN FUNC.  IF YOU WANT TO
                                    1166              *       DEAL WITH ARRAYS (IF THEY EXIST),,, GOOD LUCK HASBRO !!
                                    1167              *       A SAMPLE EXAMPLE, OR AN EXAMPLE OF A SAMPLE:
                                    1168              *
1PROC     WYLBUR System Procedures                                                                                          Page    8
0D-Loc  Object Code    Addr1 Addr2  Stmt Lv Lineno    Source Statement           (Hibal 5, Asmedit 3.3)  HLASM R4.0  2004/03/15 12.51
+_____  ______ ____    _____ _____  ____ __ ______    ______ _________
0                                   1169              *        ...   COMMENT                   RETURN PARMS
                                    1170              *              L     R6,XXRETPTR         LOAD RETURN AREA PTR
                                    1171              *              ST    R2,XXLINENO
                                    1172              *              PRETVAL 1,STRING,(R1),(R0)   RETURN A STRING
                                    1173              *              PRETVAL 2,LINENO,L:XXLINENO  RETURN A LINENO
                                    1174              *              PRETVAL 3,STRING,'OK'        ALL OK
                                    1175              *              CLEAR   R15               ALL OK
                                    1176              *              XEXIT   R0,R8,LTR         RETURN
                                    1177              *         ...
                                    1178              *        NOTE IN THIS EXAMPLE, XXRETPTR AND XXLINENO ARE ASSUMED
                                    1179              *        TO BE STORAGE IN THE PROCEDURES LOCAL WORK AREA.
                                    1180              *
                                    1181              *   *** FINAL ADVICE
                                    1182              *
                                    1183              *       THIS MODULE ADHERES TO SEVERAL CONVENTIONS.  IF YOU
                                    1184              *       ADHERE TO THESE CONVENTIONS, IT WILL MAKE IT EASIER FOR
                                    1185              *       YOU AND ANY OTHERS WHO MAY WANT TO ADD SYSTEM PROCEDURES
                                    1186              *       TO ADD THEM. IT IS WORTH IT TO TAKE A BIT OF TIME AND
                                    1187              *       LOOK AT HOW SEVERAL EXITING SYSTEM PROCEDURE ROUTINES
                                    1188              *       CODED.
                                    1189              *
                                    1190              *   *** SOME DOCUMENTATION
                                    1191              *
                                    1192              *        ON ENTRY:
                                    1193              *             R0 - VARIABLE COUNT
                                    1194              *             R1 - ARGUMENT LIST
                                    1195              *             R6 - PROCEDURE RETURN AREA
                                    1196              *                  (AREA WILL INITIALY CONTAIN PROCEDURE NAME)
                                    1197              *
                                    1198              *
                                    1199              *        ON EXIT:
                                    1200              *             R6 - RETURNED VALUES (SAME AS ON ENTRY)
                                    1201              *            R15 - CC=ZERO, ALL OK
                                    1202              *                  CC=NZ, IF ERROR,,, ERROR MSG TSEG 'D
                                    1203              *
                                    1204              *        ARG1     EQU   0*L'VPARM           USUALLY @R1
                                    1205              *        ARG2     EQU   1*L'VPARM
                                    1206              *        ARG3     EQU   2*L'VPARM
                                    1207              *        ARG4     EQU   3*L'VPARM
                                    1208              *        ARG5     EQU   4*L'VPARM
                                    1209              *        ARG6     EQU   5*L'VPARM
                                    1210              *
                                    1211              *        FNRET    EQU   0*L'VPARM           USUALLY @R6
                                    1212              *
                                    1213              *
                                    1214              *        FNWA     RECORD BEGIN ,            GENERALIZED WORK AREA !
                                    1215              *                 XSA   R0,R8
                                    1216              *        FNWORK   DS    XL(L'VPARM)         256+ BYTE WORK AREA
                                    1217              *                 END
                                    1218              *        ******************** OH YEAH !!

                                    8608              *
                                    8609              *  GETPROCP - GET SYSTEM PROCEDURE ROUTINE ADDRESS
                                    8610              *
                                    8611              *  ON ENTRY:
                                    8612              *    @R0 - PLACE TO RETURN ROUTINE ADDRESS

                                    8614              *
                                    8615              *  ON EXIT:
                                    8616              *    R15=Z, ROUTINE FOUND;  R15=NZ, ROUTINE NOT FOUND

                                    8618              *
                                    8619              *
                                    8620              *  NOTE:
                                    8621              *  IF ROUTINE POINTER IS ZERO, ROUTINE IS NOT DEFINED. THIS IS
                                    8622              *  SO THAT WE CAN CONTROL WHICH ABBREVAIATIONS FIND MATCHES.

0                                   9705              ¿þþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþÜ
                                    9706              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                    9707              Ÿ  COLLECT_SCAN -- SCAN AND PROCESS COLLECT OPTIONS                   Ÿ
                                    9708              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                    9709              Ÿ  READ INPUT STRING, STRIPING AND PROCESSING COLLECT                 Ÿ
                                    9710              Ÿ  OPTIONS.  HOW IS THIS DONE? IT IS DONE BY SCANNING                 Ÿ
                                    9711              Ÿ  THE INPUT STRING USING THE COLPRT (COLLECT OPTIONS)                Ÿ
                                    9712              Ÿ  SCAN TABLE, ALL COLLECT OPTIONS ARE SCANED OFF.                    Ÿ
                                    9713              Ÿ  OPTIONS THAT REMAIN ARE CONCATENATED TOGETHER TO                   Ÿ
                                    9714              Ÿ  FORM A NEW STRING.  AT THE CONCLUSION OF THE SCANNING              Ÿ
                                    9715              Ÿ  WE INSPECT THE DUMP PARMS THAT HAVE BEEN SET UP                    Ÿ
                                    9716              Ÿ  AND COPY THEM TO EXEC DUMP PARMS.                                  Ÿ
                                    9717              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                    9718              Ÿ  TO PROPERLY REMOVE THE SCANNED ITEMS WE MARK ALL                   Ÿ
                                    9719              Ÿ  SCANNED ITEMS WITH 'X', WE THEN MARK ALL ITEMS                     Ÿ
                                    9720              Ÿ  SCANNED EXCLUDING THE COLLECT ITEMS WITH A 'Y'.                    Ÿ
                                    9721              Ÿ  BY REMOVING ALL THE 'X' ITEMS WE COMPLETE OUR                      Ÿ
                                    9722              Ÿ  TASK.  BUF1 IS THE 'X' 'Y' SHADOW BUFFER.                          Ÿ
                                    9723              Ÿ  RET1 WILL BE THE STRING TO RETURN.  SSTR IS THE                    Ÿ
                                    9724              Ÿ  COPY OF THE STRING WE USE FOR THE SCAN.                            Ÿ
                                    9725              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                    9726              Ÿ  FOR EXAMPLE:                                                       Ÿ
                                    9727              Ÿ  STRING:  OPT1 OPT2 COLLECT END+12 OPT3 CLEAR OPT4                  Ÿ
                                    9728              Ÿ  BUF1:    YYYY YYYY XXXXXXX XXXXXX YYYY XXXXX YYYY                  Ÿ
                                    9729              Ÿ  RET1:    OPT1 OPT2 OPT3 OPT4                                       Ÿ
                                    9730              Ÿ  RET2:    COLLECT END+12 CLEAR                                      Ÿ
                                    9731              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                    9732              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                                      ¾þþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþ»

0                                  54077              ¿þþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþÜ
                                   54078              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   54079              Ÿ   SCAN_MAILHDR -- Scan RFC-822 mail header                          Ÿ
                                   54080              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   54081              Ÿ     On entry, current active file contains mail item                Ÿ
                                   54082              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   54083              Ÿ     On exit, scanned mail header fields are returned in an active   Ÿ
                                   54084              Ÿ     file containing lines with the following format:                Ÿ
                                   54085              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   54086              Ÿ       col 1-16 - field name from header                             Ÿ
                                   54087              Ÿ       col 18   - address type indicator                             Ÿ
                                   54088              Ÿ                  'f' if from, sender, reply-to, or errors-to        Ÿ
                                   54089              Ÿ                  't' if to, cc, or bcc                              Ÿ
                                   54090              Ÿ       col 20+  - field contents                                     Ÿ
                                   54091              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   54092              Ÿ     Arguments:                                                      Ÿ
                                   54093              Ÿ       1 - on entry, output active file number (or zero)             Ÿ
                                   54094              Ÿ       2 - on entry, options string                                  Ÿ
                                   54095              Ÿ       3 - on exit, last line of header                              Ÿ
                                   54096              Ÿ       4 - on exit, return code ('OK' or 'ERROR')                    Ÿ
                                   54097              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   54098              Ÿ     Options:                                                        Ÿ
                                   54099              Ÿ       debug  - turn on debugging option                             Ÿ
                                   54100              Ÿ       nolist - suppress listing header lines as they are read       Ÿ
                                   54101              Ÿ       noptr  - suppress 'pointers' lines in output file             Ÿ
                                   54102              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                                      ¾þþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþ»

1PROC     (PROC2193) (12:51) (15MAR04) Common Routines for System Procedures                                                Page  225
0Current Usings:  (CP,R11) (CV,R12)
0Loc    Object Code    Addr1 Addr2  Stmt Lv Lineno    Source Statement           (Hibal 5, Asmedit 3.3)  HLASM R4.0  2004/03/15 12.51

0                                  63553              ¿þþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþþÜ
                                   63554              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   63555              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   63556              Ÿ  MATCHBUF - MATCH LINES IN BUFFER                                   Ÿ
                                   63557              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   63558              Ÿ  THE MAIN IDEA OF THIS ROUTINE IS TO FIND A SPOT WHERE THE          Ÿ
                                   63559              Ÿ  TWO BUFFERS HAVE LINES THAT MATCH.  THIS IS DONE ESSENTIALLY       Ÿ
                                   63560              Ÿ  BY RUBBING THE TWO BUFFERS TOGETHER AND CHECKING FOR A             Ÿ
                                   63561              Ÿ  MATCH.  MORE SPECIFICALLY, WE COMPARE ALL THE LINES IN             Ÿ
                                   63562              Ÿ  BUFFER 2 WITH THE FIRST LINE IN BUFFER 1.  THEN WE COMPARE         Ÿ
                                   63563              Ÿ  ALL THE LINES IN BUFFER 2 WITH THE SECOND LINE IN BUFFER 1.        Ÿ
                                   63564              Ÿ   .... AND SO ON ... AND SO ON.  WHEN WE FIND LINES THAT            Ÿ
                                   63565              Ÿ  MATCH WE DO A MORE THOROUGH MATCH CHECK AND EXIT IF THE            Ÿ
                                   63566              Ÿ  LINES MATCH.  A COUNT OPTION IS SPECIFIED, AND WE ONLY             Ÿ
                                   63567              Ÿ  COMPARE TO THAT DEPTH.                                             Ÿ
                                   63568              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   63569              Ÿ  ON ENTRY:                                                          Ÿ
                                   63570              Ÿ       R0 - BUFFER #1 ADDRESS                                        Ÿ
                                   63571              Ÿ       R1 - BUFFER #1 LENGTH                                         Ÿ
                                   63572              Ÿ       R2 - BUFFER #2 ADDRESS                                        Ÿ
                                   63573              Ÿ       R3 - BUFFER #2 LENGTH                                         Ÿ
                                   63574              Ÿ       R4 - BUFFER #1 LINE NUMBERS                                   Ÿ
                                   63575              Ÿ       R5 - BUFFER #2 LINE NUMBERS                                   Ÿ
                                   63576              Ÿ       R6 - COMPARE DEPTH COUNT                                      Ÿ
                                   63577              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   63578              Ÿ  ON EXIT:                                                           Ÿ
                                   63579              Ÿ       R0 - LINENO THAT MATCHES IN BUFFER #1 (R15=0)                 Ÿ
                                   63580              Ÿ       R1 - LINENO THAT MATCHES IN BUFFER #2 (R15=0)                 Ÿ
                                   63581              Ÿ      R15 - CC=ZERO, MATCH FOUND                                     Ÿ
                                   63582              Ÿ            CC=NZ, NO MATCH FOUND                                    Ÿ
                                   63583              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   63584              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   63585              Ÿ  BUFFER FORMAT:                                                     Ÿ
                                   63586              Ÿ       FILLED WITH TEXT LINES, EACH LINE CONSISTS OF:                Ÿ
                                   63587              Ÿ          4 BYTES TEXT LENGTH = N                                    Ÿ
                                   63588              Ÿ          N BYTES TEXT                                               Ÿ
                                   63589              Ÿ  LINE NUMBER BUFFER FORMAT:                                         Ÿ
                                   63590              Ÿ       FILLED WITH 4 BYTE LINE NUMBERS,  EOF IS =F'-1'               Ÿ
                                   63591              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   63592              Ÿ                                                                     Ÿ
                                   63593              Ÿ  NOTES:  LINE NUMBER BUFFER MUST BE 4*MAX NO OF LINES, LONG.        Ÿ
